            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Valerio is a product of two distinct, fragrant worlds. Born in Daly City to a Filipino mother, a pragmatic nurse, and a second-generation Italian-American father, a passionate baker, Mateo\u2019s childhood was a blend of his mother\u2019s quiet diligence and the boisterous art of his father\u2019s panetteria. He didn't grow up surrounded by fine art, but by the craft of survival and the beauty of well-made things, from a perfectly baked focaccia to a precisely dressed wound. This foundation steered him not toward creating art, but toward protecting and presenting it.\n\nHe pursued a practical path at San Francisco State University, earning a degree in Arts Administration that satisfied both his artistic sensibilities and his inherited pragmatism. His career began in the grant-writing trenches of non-profits, but a key turning point came during the first dot-com boom. He took a job with a short-lived but visionary startup attempting to digitize museum collections. The company folded, but the experience ignited Mateo\u2019s passion for merging technology with tangible art, a focus that would define his career.\n\nNow, as the Director of Exhibitions for a prestigious downtown design and technology museum, Mateo is at the pinnacle of his profession. His days are a whirlwind of budgets, artist negotiations, and spatial logistics. He takes the Muni K/T line 3.8 miles from his meticulously curated Hayes Valley apartment, a commute he uses for reading exhibition catalogs on his tablet. His life is orderly and intentional.\n\nSocially, Mateo maintains a tight circle of friends\u2014a mix of academics, chefs, and fellow art professionals\u2014who gather for dinners where conversations are as rich as the food. A decade-long relationship ended amicably five years ago, leaving him with a deeper appreciation for his own company and a quiet solitude he now cherishes. His current dream isn't about personal gain but about legacy. He's focused on mentoring emerging curators and plans to helm a groundbreaking international exhibition on bio-art that he believes will be his masterwork. For Mateo, San Francisco is more than a home; it's his primary medium, an ever-shifting gallery he is honored to help shape."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, standing on a stool in the warm, yeasty air of the panetteria. His father\u2019s flour-dusted hands showed him yeast blooming in water\u2014a quiet, living magic. Just then, his mother walked in from her nursing shift, the clean, sharp scent of antiseptic on her scrubs cutting through the doughy comfort. The collision of smells wasn't jarring, but clarifying. In that moment, he understood that creating life and preserving it were the same fundamental, careful act. This fusion of craft and care became his internal compass.\n\n2.\nEarly 2001. The startup office was a graveyard of Aeron chairs and dead monitors. His final task was shutting down the servers. He watched a pixel-perfect scan of a Botticelli fresco, vibrant and detailed on the screen, disappear into black. The sudden silence of the server fans was deafening. He didn't feel failure, but a fierce, defining clarity. The digital ghost needed a physical home; the image needed a stage. That moment wasn't an end, but the true beginning of his life's work merging art with technology.\n\n3.\nFive years ago, he and Javier sat on the hardwood floor, dividing not assets, but their library. Surrounded by spines that told the story of their decade together, there were no tears, just a quiet, respectful sorting. Handing over a beloved art monograph, Mateo felt not a brutal loss, but a careful rearrangement. The silence that followed Javier\u2019s departure wasn\u2019t empty, but a clean, open gallery space. He learned then that solitude, like an exhibition, could be curated into something beautiful and intentional.\n\n4.\nIt was a Tuesday morning on his K/T commute, stalled on the portal just before Embarcadero. Rain blurred the city lights into abstract expressionism on the window. Inside, the impatient, diverse, resilient cross-section of San Francisco was its own installation. He looked down at the catalog on his tablet, then back at the faces around him. He wasn't just observing his city; he was a component within it. San Francisco wasn't just his home; it was the raw, chaotic, beautiful material he was privileged to shape.\n\n5.\nTwo years ago, a shy intern nervously questioned his layout for an exhibit, pointing to the foam-core model and suggesting a flow that was counter-intuitive but brilliant. In her hesitant explanation, Mateo didn't hear a challenge, but an echo of his own younger passion. He saw that the most enduring exhibition he could build was not of objects, but of people. His ambition instantly shifted from building his name to building the next generation, ensuring the gallery\u2019s future would be bolder than his own."
